'''John M. Chambers''' is the creator of the [[S (programming language)|S programming language]], and core member of the [[R (programming language)|R programming language]] project. He was awarded the 1998 [[ACM Software System Award]] for developing S.<ref>[http://www.acm.org/announcements/ss99.html/ ACM honors Dr. John M. Chambers of Bell Labs with the 1998 ACM Software System Award for creating "S System" software], ACM press release, March 29, 1999. Accessed 8 December 2008.</ref> He donated his prize money (US$10,000) to the [[American Statistical Association]] to endow an award for novel statistical software.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stat-computing.org/awards/jmc/history.html |title=John M. Chambers Statistical Software Award. ASA Statistics Computing and Graphics |work= |accessdate=}}</ref>

Chambers is a [[Fellow]] of the [[American Statistical Association]], the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] and the [[Institute of Mathematical Statistics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stat.bell-labs.com/jmc/vitae.html |title=John M. Chambers - Vitae | publisher = [[Bell Laboratories]]}}</ref>

He was a Consulting Professor of Statistics at Stanford University.<ref>[http://www-stat.stanford.edu/people/faculty/chambers/index.html Stanford University Department of Statistics Page for John M. Chambers.] Accessed January 16, 2010.</ref> He received a B.Sc. from the [[University of Toronto]] and M.A. and Ph.D. degrees in Statistics from [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=John M. Chambers - Vitae|website=http://stat.bell-labs.com/jmc/vitae.html}}</ref>

